\begin_layout Section
Resource Management
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Resource management in more general terms can be defined in similar terms
 to the four basic functions of persistent data storage: creation, reading,
 updating, and deletion of resources (CRUD
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CRUD"
description "Creation, Reading, Updating, and Deletion"

\end_inset

).
 Resource managment is a very broad topic and as applies to schools or,
 more specifically, colleges or univerities has three perspectives that
 make up the bigger picture: facility management, human resource management
 and quality management (certification).
 Each perspective brings with it its own resources and emphasis in usage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These four activities take on different aspects dependant upon the resource
 upon which they are applied and are known under differing names.
 For example, creation in terms of material objects is generally refered
 to as aquisition, whereas in terms of personel as hiring.
 Reading in terms of documentation is self explaining, but in terms of other
 resources it could be seen as the browsing of a telephone book, or performing
 cost calculations in a spreadsheet program.
 Updating would be the refurbishment of a room, the further education of
 an employee, or the modification of documentation among other things.
 Deletion could be the simple removal of software, or the demolition of
 a building.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As can be gleaned from the previous examples resource managment in the broadest
 sense encompasses such topics as human resources management, facility managemen
t, document management and many other fields at the level of the university
 level.
 Resource management within this thesis will focus mainly on the topic of
 scheduling.
 This aspect is unique in that it has in and of itself has no resources
 per se and takes place at a high level of abstraction.
 It is an association of resources aquired through other resource management
 processes.
 Its resources are lessons, events, appointments, meetings, speeches, etc.;
 they tell us who does what, when, where, for whom, and under certain circumstan
ces it even gives us a glimpse as to how.
\end_layout

